@node Requirements

  @{b}- Requirements -@{ub}

Helene requires an Amiga with OS 3.0 or higher (it is only tested with
OS 3.9). In addition it requires the following four files:

  Gui         -  Needed for running Helene.
  Gui4Cli     -  Needed for running Helene.
  WBPatWrite  -  Required for creating WB Pattern preset files.
  RandyProg   -  Used for selecting a WB Pattern preset file at random.


All files are included in this distribution. For more information, take 
a look at the @{"Installation" link Installation} section.


@endnode


@node Installation

  @{b}- Installation -@{ub}

To install Helene, just follow the instructions below:

 1. Copy Gui & Gui4Cli to C: on your boot partition.
 2. Extract "WBPatWrite" from the "wbpw.lha" archive and copy it to C:
 3. Extract "RandyProg" from the "RandyProg.lha" archive and copy it to C:
 4. Copy Helene to where ever you want on your harddisk.

The "wbpw.lha" and "RandyProg.lha" archives are located in the "Extra"
directory of this distribution.

If you are afraid of cluttering up your C: dir with all kind of files,
you can copy "WBPatWrite" to the same dir as Helene instead.



  @{b}- Installation of the Scripts -@{ub}

Included in this distribution there are two Shell scripts:

 SelectWB-BG  -  Used for selecting a WB Pattern preset file from a requester.
 RandomWB-BG  -  Used for selecting a WB Pattern preset file at random.

The best location for these two files are probably S: on your boot partition.


If you want to have a WB Pattern preset file selected at random each time 
you boot your Amiga, you can probably copy the "RandomWB-BG" file to the 
"WBStartup" directory on your boot partition, but the most effective way is 
to include a line in your Startup-Sequence. Use a text editor (like Ed) and 
open your Startup-Sequence file (which is located in S:), then add the
following line somewhere between the Env: creation stuff and the "C:IPrefs"
line:

 Execute >NIL: S:RandomWB-BG

Then save your Startup-Sequence.

Please Note! It is recommended that you edit Helenes Settings and create 
some WB Pattern preset files @{i}before@{ui} you do this.

@endnode




@node HeleneUsage "Helene Usage"

                    @{b}---++-   Helene  1.0   -++---@{ub}

                         @{b}     U s a g e     @{ub}



This section explains how you can use Helene for managing your WBPattern 
preset files. If you never have used Helene before, it's recommended that 
you read the @{"Important" link Important} page before you continue.


  @{b}- The Listview -@{ub}
This shows a list over all your WBPattern preset files. If you click on a 
file, Helene will automatically read the names of the Workbench and Windows 
pictures from it. These names will then appear in the text gadgets below the 
listview.

  @{b}- Apply -@{ub}
When you press this button, Helene will apply the selected WBPattern preset
file to your system, this in turn will change the Workbench and Windows 
backdrops to the ones described in the preset file.

  @{b}- Test -@{ub}
This button allows you to test the currently selected picture files on your
Workbench without having to save a WB pattern preset first. It is ideal for
testing out Workbench and Windows picture combinations.

  @{b}- Copy -@{ub}
This will make a copy of the currently selected preset file, the name of the
new copy will be the same as the original one, but it will have "Copy of" 
appended at the beginning of the file name. If this file already exists,
"Copy X of" will be appended instead (where X represents a number).

  @{b}- Delete -@{ub}
The Delete button will as you probably already have guessed, delete the 
currently selected preset file :-)

  @{b}- Save -@{ub}
By pressing this button, Helene will save a preset file which will contain 
the names of the pictures you have selected for Workbench & Windows backdrops.
The name of this preset file will be the one you have entered in the "Preset"
text gadget. Have in mind that Helene WILL overwrite an existing file without
asking you first!



  @{b}- Preset -@{ub}
This text gadget shows the name of the currently selected WB Pattern preset
file. If you want to create a new preset file, just enter the name of a non-
existing file in this gadget. Then it will be created when you press the
Save button (just remember to select some pictures first :-)
The "R" button on the right will re-read the information from the preset file.

  @{b}- WB Pic -@{ub}
Here you can select the picture to be used as Workbench backdrop, just enter
the name (including the FULL path) in the text gadget or press the button
on the right to pop up a file requester. 

  @{b}- Win Pic -@{ub}
Here you can select the picture to be used as Windows backdrop, just enter
the name (including the FULL path) in the text gadget or press the button
on the right to pop up a file requester. 
 


  @{b}- Update LV -@{ub}
This button will update the Listview, this is in case some changes has been
made to the directory used for the WB Pattern preset files. Usually Helene 
will be notified by any changes made to this dir and will automatically update
the listview, but since I have decided to include an option for turning this
functionality off in the @{"Settings" link HeleneSettings} GUI, I thought that it would be a good idea
to include this button.

  @{b}- Iconify & Quit -@{ub}
I will not bother with explaining the Iconify & Quit buttons since I'm sure 
that you already understand what they will do :-)

@endnode


@node HeleneMenu "Helene Menu"

                    @{b}---++-   Helene  1.0   -++---@{ub}

                          @{b}    M e n u s    @{ub}



This section explains how to use the Menus of Helene.


    @{b}- Project Menu -@{ub}

  @{b}- About Helene -@{ub}
This menu item will show you some information about Helene.

  @{b}- WBPattern Prefs -@{ub}
If you select this menu item, Helene will open the WBPattern Prefs program
with the currently selected WB Pattern preset file. This is so that you can
configure various advanced settings (that is not supported by Helene).

  @{b}- Helene Settings -@{ub}
By selecting this menu item, Helene will open it's @{"Settings" link HeleneSettings} window where you
can configure various things about Helene.

  @{b}- Iconify & Quit -@{ub}
I will not bother with explaining the Iconify & Quit menu items since I'm 
sure that you already understand what they will do :-)



    @{b}- Action Menu -@{ub}

  @{b}- Apply Preset -@{ub}
When you select this menu item, Helene will apply the selected WBPattern 
preset file to your system, this in turn will change the Workbench and 
Windows backdrops to the ones described in the preset file.

  @{b}- Test Pictures -@{ub}
This menu item allows you to test the currently selected picture files on 
your Workbench without having to save a WB pattern preset first. It is ideal
for testing out Workbench and Windows picture combinations.

  @{b}- Copy Preset -@{ub}
This will make a copy of the currently selected preset file, the name of the
new copy will be the same as the original one, but it will have "Copy of" 
appended at the beginning of the file name. If this file already exists,
"Copy X of" will be appended instead (where X represents a number).

  @{b}- Delete Preset -@{ub}
The Delete menu item will as you probably already have guessed, delete the 
currently selected preset file :-)

  @{b}- Rename Preset -@{ub}
This allows you to rename the currently selected WB Pattern preset file.

  @{b}- Save Preset -@{ub}
By selecting this item, Helene will save a preset file which will contain 
the names of the pictures you have selected for Workbench & Windows backdrops.
The name of this preset file will be the one you have entered in the "Preset"
text gadget. Have in mind that Helene WILL overwrite an existing file without
asking you first!



    @{b}- View Menu -@{ub}

  @{b}- View WB Picture -@{ub}
Select this menu item if you want to view the picture that you have chosen
to be used as Workbench backdrop. The program used for viewing is the one
selected in the @{"Settings" link HeleneSettings} GUI (the default is MultiView).

  @{b}- View Win Picture -@{ub}
This will view the picture chosen to be used as Windows backdrop. 

@endnode


@node HeleneSettings "Helene Settings"

                    @{b}---++-   Helene  1.0   -++---@{ub}

                         @{b}  S e t t i n g s  @{ub}



This section explains how to use the Settings GUI where you can configure
various things about Helene.


  @{b}- Presets Dir -@{ub}
This is the most important thing to configure. Here you select the directory
to be used for the WB Pattern preset files you create, the path to this dir 
will be saved into an Env variable called @{b}HelenePresetsPath@{ub} which will be 
used by both Helene and the SelectWB-BG & RandomWB-BG scripts. Remember that 
if you decide to configure this variable manually, do NOT include quotation 
marks in it!

  @{b}- Pictures Dir -@{ub}
Here you can select the directory that contains the picture files that you 
want to use as Workbench backdrops. Every time you open a file requester for 
selecting a file, it will open with this directory selected (only when no
picture has previously been selected).

  @{b}- Patterns Dir -@{ub}
Here you can select the directory that contains the picture files that you 
want to use as Windows backdrops. Every time you open a file requester for 
selecting a file, it will open with this directory selected (only when no
picture has previously been selected).



  @{b}- Win BG Pic -@{ub}
Allows you to select the picture to be used as background for Helenes GUI.

  @{b}- Pic Viewer -@{ub}
Select the Viewer program to be used for viewing pictures (the default is
MultiView). The "Args" text gadget allows you to enter additional arguments
to be used on the command line.



  @{b}- Auto-Update ListView -@{ub}
If you enable this option, Helene will automatically update it's listview if
any changes (not performed by Helene) has been made to the WB Pattern presets 
dir. There may be times when this can be a bit annoying, so when this happens, 
you can turn this functionality off. Helene will still update the listview
when it is used to perform changes to files in the dir, but you will have to
press the "Update LV" button if you do any manually changes.

  @{b}- Create Icons -@{ub}
By enabling this option, an icon will be created for the WB Pattern preset 
file when it is saved. The default tool is set to SYS:Prefs/WBPattern and a 
tooltype ACTION=USE is set. First the WBPatWrite program seeks for a file 
ENV:Sys/def_pref.info to use. If this is not found, the system default 
project icon is used.

@endnode



@node Important

  @{b}- Important -@{ub}

Before using Helene, please take your time and note the following:

When you start Helene for the very first time, a requester will pop up and
tell you that no directory has been selected for your WB Pattern Preset files.

You must select this dir before you start creating Preset files with Helene,
just open Helenes Settings GUI (by choosing "Helene Settings" in the Project
menu) and select the dir to be used in the "Presets Dir" gadget. Then click
on the Save button to make this permanent.

If a directory called "Presets" can be found in the same dir as Helene, this
dir will automatically be used as the Presets dir, but this setting will NOT
be permanent, to do this you will have to save it in the Settings GUI. 

The location and the name of the directory to be used for WB Pattern Preset
files is entirely up to you, Personally I have created a directory called
"BG Presets" in Prefs/Presets/ of my boot partition for this purpose.


One last thing: Remember that the directory you select for Preset files can
ONLY contain WB Pattern Preset files, the only exception to this is Icons.


@endnode



@node StartingHelene "Starting Helene"

  @{b}- Starting Helene -@{ub}

This section describes how to start Helene.

  @{b}- Starting from Workbench -@{ub}
Just double-click the Helene icon. Remember that if you change the icon
to another one, the Default Tool of the new icon MUST be set to "Gui".


  @{b}- Starting from Shell -@{ub}
You can start Helene in a Shell by typing "Gui Helene".

@endnode



@node ScriptsInfo "Scripts Information"

   @{b}- Scripts Information -@{ub}

This section contains some info about the RandomWB-BG & SelectWB-BG scripts.

These scripts have one thing in common, they will both look for a file in 
Env: called @{b}HelenePresetsPath@{ub}. This file will be used as an Env variable,
and the contents of it should be the full path to the directory used for the
WB Pattern preset files.
It is really important that you configure this @{i}before@{ui} you use these scripts,
you can either use Helenes @{"Settings" link HeleneSettings} GUI for configuring it, or you can do it
yourself manually, just remember that you can't use quotation marks in the
variable.


  @{b}- RandomWB-BG -@{ub}
This script is used for selecting a random WB Pattern preset file.
It is designed to be as quiet as possible since it is meant to be used during 
booting of the Amiga, this means that it will never report any error messages.

First it will create a text file called RandomWB-BG_List in T: by using the
List command on your WB Pattern presets dir (the path to this dir will be read
from the Env variable described above), this text file will contain a list 
over all your WB Pattern preset files. Then RandyProg will be used to pick one
file at random from this list, and this preset file will then be copied to
Env:Sys where it also will be renamed to wbpattern.prefs.

The last thing that happens is that the script cleans up by deleting the file
T:RandomWB-BG_List (this is because it is only a temporary file).

I know that many of you will not quite agree with the way the List command is
used in this script since a new file has to be created each time the script is
run, but I have decided to make it very easy to use, and besides, it only 
takes a second to list all my preset files (which consists of 60 files at the
moment).

Another thing that you might not like is the way that the script checks if
everything is present, you might consider this to be a bit unnecessary, but I
have also decided to make it as safe as possible to use in addition to easy.
This way the chances of it aborting the booting of your Amiga will be smaller
(if you use the script in your Startup-Sequence that is).


If you don't like the way this script works, here is an alternative to it:

You can make a permanent list over all your WB Pattern preset files by 
entering the following in a Shell:

 List "$HelenePresetsPath" FILES PAT "~(#?.info)" QUICK NOHEAD LFORMAT "*"%P%N*"" >S:RandomWB-BG_List

Or if you don't want to use the HelenePresetsPath Env variable, you can enter
the following (if the path to your Presets are Sys:Prefs/Presets/BGPresets):

 List "Sys:Prefs/Presets/BGPresets" FILES PAT "~(#?.info)" QUICK NOHEAD LFORMAT "*"%P%N*"" >S:RandomWB-BG_List

Both will create the file RandomWB-BG_List in S: which will contain a list
over all your WB Pattern Preset files. The negative thing with doing things
this way is that you must repeat this process every time some changes are made
to the presets dir. It is really recommended that you create a new script file
which contains one of the lines above to make things easier for yourself.


For selecting a random WB Pattern Preset file by using the RandomWB-BG_List
file described above, enter the following in a Shell (or create a script
which contains this line):

 RandyProg "Copy TO Env:Sys/wbpattern.prefs" S:RandomWB-BG_List

This line can also be entered in your Startup-Sequence instead of the one
described in the @{"Installation" link Installation} section, just remember to insert it somewhere
between the Env: creation stuff and the C:IPrefs line.



  @{b}- SelectWB-BG -@{ub}
This script allows you to select a WB Pattern preset file from a requester.
Unlike the RandomWB-BG script, this one will report any error message it comes
across. If nothing happens when running RandomWB-BG, try this script instead
to see if it can give you a clue about the problem.

It uses the CLI RequestFile command to open a file requester from where you
can select a preset file. Then the script will try to copy the selected preset
file to Env:Sys, it will also try to rename the file to wbpattern.prefs.
This in turn will cause the system to use the information found in the preset
file to update your Workbench and Windows background.

As with the RandomWB-BG script, you can probably come up with your own
solution if you're not quite satisfied with the way it works.


@endnode


@node PicsInfo "Pictures Information"

   @{b}- Pictures Information -@{ub}

This section contains some information about the included pictures.

I decided to include three of the pictures that I use as Workbench backdrops
in the Helene distribution, you can find them in the Backdrops directory. All
of them have the size of 800 x 600 pixels.
I have also included some of the pictures that I use as Windows backgrounds,
these can be found in the Patterns directory.

If you are interested in some of the other pictures that I use as Workbench
backgrounds, check out the Pictures section of my website at www.home.no/rhz


Here are some more info about the pics:

  @{b}- Guru Meditation.iff -@{ub}
I guess you are wondering about how I managed to make this screen grab, well
it was very simple really, it was done when my PC was running WinUAE (yes I
know - shame on me :-) while I was trying to boot an old A500 game. It did
not work and the emulated Amiga crashed. Then I got the idea to make this
grab, I later used PPaint to resize the picture and I also reduced the
amount of colors used in it from 256 to 2.

I use the BoingInTheBlue.ilbm picture as Windows pattern with this picture.


  @{b}- Himmel & Hav.jpg -@{ub}
This one was taken with a really crap digital camera I once had, this camera
could only be considered to be nothing more than a toy and I later bought a
real digital camera instead. The major problem with the original picture was
the low resolution it was in, I really tried my best to improve the image
quality after resizing it, but the resulting image still turned out to be a
bit pixelated. Nevertheless, it is still a picture that I like and if nothing
else, I can always use it as a reminder to not expect miracles when buying
cheap products.   By the way, Himmel & Hav is norwegian for Heaven & Ocean.

I use the Sand.iff picture as Windows pattern with this picture.


  @{b}- Troll Church.jpg -@{ub}
There is a story behind this picture: For about ten years ago I walked up a
mountain together with a friend of mine and his girlfriend. Since I was (and
still are) not in a very good condition, they were a little faster than me.
This resulted in them reaching the top long before me, but before they did
that, they went inside a cave. When they wanted to go out again, they had 
some problems with finding the way out, this was because they did not bring
along a flashlight and they had to stumble around in the dark. But since my
friend had a camera with him, he used it to take some pictures, the reason
for this was to use the flash lamp as guidance. And this picture is one of
those he took.

A couple of years later, I bought my scanner and was looking for something
to test it on. I found this picture and decided to scan it. I was so pleased
with the result that I decided to use it as a background on my Workbench.

I use the Leather.iff picture as Windows pattern with this picture.


@endnode


@node Limitations "Limitations"

   @{b}- Limitations -@{ub}

Helene has the following limitations:


  @{b}-  I  -@{ub}
Amiga OS 3.5 introduced a more advanced WBPattern Prefs program which allowed
the user to configure the Dither Quality, Color Quality and the Layout of the
pictures to be used as WB backgrounds. None of these options is supported by 
Helene, this is because of limitations of the WBPatWrite program (which is 
used to create WB Pattern preset files). If you really need to configure these
options, you can use the WBPattern program directly on your preset files, just
have in mind that if you select a preset file in Helene and you save it, these
options WILL be ignored and none of them will be written to the new file.

WBPattern Prefs will automatically use these defaults on preset files which 
lacks the new options:

  Dither Quality  =  Good
  Color Quality   =  Good
  Layout          =  Tile


  @{b}-  II  -@{ub}
WBPattern Prefs allows the user to select a picture to be used as Screen 
background, this is usually only seen when the Workbench is not in backdrop
mode. Helene does not support this function since I'm sure that the majority
of Amiga users run their Workbench in backdrop mode (this is based upon all 
the various WB screenshots I have seen over the years).


  @{b}-  III  -@{ub}
Another thing that is not supported in Helene is preset files which contains
patterns that are drawn by using the WBPattern Prefs program. When Helene 
reads such a preset file, it will think that no pictures have been selected
and the "WB Pic" & "Win Pic" text gadgets will turn up empty. If you later 
decide to save the preset, the patterns in it will be overwritten.

My personal opinion is that the time is long overdue for removing the pattern
drawing function from the WBPattern Prefs program. It was once useful back in
the times when Amiga OS 2.x was standard and most people used screen modes 
with low resolutions, but I think that it simply doesn't belong in a modern OS.
I really hope that it will be removed in Amiga OS 4.


  @{b}-  IV  -@{ub}
While the writing of WB Pattern preset files is done by WBPatWrite, the 
reading of them is done internally by Helene. I have tried to make this as
fast as possible, but it has led to one little problem: If no WB picture was 
selected when the preset file was saved, Helene will not be able to read the
name of the Win picture.


  @{b}-  IV  -@{ub}
You can't use Wildcard Characters (`()#?~%|*') in the file name of WBPattern 
preset files since it might lead to problems with using the RandomWB-BG script.
As a matter of fact, it's recommended that you don't use any of these type of
characters at all in file & directory names.


@endnode


@node PrgInformasjon "Program Information"

   @{b}- Program Information -@{ub}

Helene was made by using D. Keletsekis's Gui4Cli 3.8.
Gui4Cli is an easy scripted language for creating & running GUIs.
If you want to get hold of the whole package for making your own ones,
it can be found :

  - on AmiNet, under Dev/Gui/Gui4Cli.lha, or 
  - at D. Keletsekis's web page, http://users.hol.gr/~dck/gcmain.htm


@endnode


